it's a bit hacky but I got something to work using some `@bind` magic. the js function from `OfflineHTMLExport` didn't play nice for some reason, but this shows that it's possible in theory to get access to the DOM content in julia:
```@bind x html"""
&lt;input type="string" id="domdump"/&gt;
&lt;script&gt;
	const input = document.body.querySelector("[id=domdump]");
	input.value = document.body.querySelector('pluto-notebook').outerHTML;
&lt;/script&gt;
"""```

